[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code, let\'s build a mental model of how voice agents actually work. And by the end of this lesson, you\'ll understand which components make up a real-time voice agent, how they interact, and why latency is such a big deal. Throughout'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this workshop, you\'ll build a production quality voice assistant. It listens to callers in real time through LifeKit\'s Web RTC infrastructure. It streams speech to text, runs responses through'

[03:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an LLM, and converts them back to speech with texttospech. You\'ll add interruption handling using voice activity detection and semantic turn detection. And you\'ll wire up tool calls, conversation escalation, and'

[03:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'metric collection. Every voice agent follows the same highle pipeline. There are four core components. Voice activity detection determines when the human is speaking. Without it, your agent wastes'

[03:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'money uh processing silence and might interrupt the user mid-sentence. Speech to text transcribes audio into tokens the LLM can understand. You\'ll want to choose models that support your target'

[04:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'languages and accents. The large language model generates the reply, prompts, planning, and tool integrations all live here. And text to speech converts the LLM response into audio'

[04:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that feels natural and on brand. Supporting components like background noise cancellation, noise suppression, and end of turn detectors help the agent behave like a good conversational'

[04:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'partner. And you\'ll add several of these throughout the workshop. Now, the cascaded pipeline bad to ST to LLM to TTS shown here is currently the most popular approach. But there is an'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'alternative and that is to use speechtoech or real-time models that can process audio directly without explicit transcription. Now that\'s not going to be covered here in this workshop, but'

[04:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look out for more videos on that subject coming very soon. Now humans expect conversational latency under 500 milliseconds. Every component in the pipeline adds delay. VAD is the fastest'

[05:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at 15 to 30 milliseconds. ST takes 200 to 600 milliseconds. Uh LLMs range from 100 milliseconds to a full second. TTS adds another 100 to 300 milliseconds.'

[05:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And so these all add up. And so you could be looking at anywhere from 400 milliseconds to 2 seconds total. Hey, how\'s it going? Good. How are you? I\'m good. Just got'

[05:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'back from lunch. What did you have? A burrito. Was it good? Yeah, it was pretty good.'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I love burritos. Cool. Anything else you\'d like to talk about? You know what? I I got to go. That felt'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'painful, right? Each 2C delay adds up fast. In a real conversation, you\'d probably give up after the second or third pause. Your users will do the same thing. Low latency agents keep pipelines'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'streaming and parallel. They avoid blocking I/IO and they carefully choose providers that balance quality with speed. And you\'ll learn techniques for shaving off those milliseconds in later'

[06:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'lessons. A real-time voice has uh different networking needs than text. Let\'s compare the options. HTTP over TCP is great for text request responses, but it has a problem for live audio. You'

[06:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see, TCP guarantees that packets arrive in order. If one packet gets lost, everything behind it has to wait until that packet is resent and received. That\'s called head of line blocking. For'

[06:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a web page, that\'s fine. For live speech, a 200 millisecond pause while waiting for a retransmit on a single packet ruins the entire experience. The other option is websockets. Web soockets'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are persistent and birectional, but they\'re still blocked by TCP retransmits under poor networking conditions. But then we have web RTC over UDP and which was designed for media. UDP doesn\'t'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'guarantee packet order or delivery, which sounds bad until you realize that for live audio, skipping a lost packet is actually better than waiting for it. WebRTC builds smart handling on top of'

[07:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'UDP. It uses Opus, a codec optimized for speech that compresses audio efficiency. Each packet carries a time stamp so the receiver knows exactly when to play it.'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'A jitter buffer smooths out timing variations when packets arrive at uneven intervals. And an adaptive bit rate adjusts audio quality on the fly based on network conditions. All of this adds'

[07:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'up to low latency even when the network isn\'t cooperating. So in practice, WebRTC lets your agent deliver first audio faster and stay responsive during packet loss and jitter. This workshop'

